                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.51/566</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fletcher</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">on Duty in the Department of State, to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Thomas W. Lamont</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 27, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Lamont</hi>: I have submitted your letter of
                    December 23rd last, on the subject of the composition of the International
                    Bankers Committee on Mexican Affairs, to Mr. Polk, who is Acting Secretary of
                    State in the absence of Mr. Lansing, and he authorizes me to inform you that the
                    Department is willing to leave the details of the composition of the Committee
                    to your judgment, provided always that the effective control of policy remains
                    in our hands.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry P. Fletcher</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
